  "prompt": "What is the minimum level of mathematical proficiency required to graduate from West Point?",
  "response": "To graduate from the United States Military Academy (USMA) at West Point, cadets are required to achieve a minimum level of mathematical proficiency as part of the rigorous academic curriculum. Specifically, West Point mandates that all cadets complete a sequence of core mathematics courses, which typically include:\n\n1. **Calculus I** (MA101 or equivalent) - This course covers differential calculus, including limits, derivatives, and their applications.\n2. **Calculus II** (MA102 or equivalent) - This course covers integral calculus, including techniques of integration, applications, and an introduction to sequences and series.\n3. **Probability and Statistics** (MA104 or equivalent) - This course introduces fundamental concepts in probability theory and statistical methods.\n\nThese courses are designed to ensure that cadets have a solid foundation in mathematical reasoning and problem-solving skills, which are essential for their future roles as military officers and leaders. Cadets are expected to demonstrate competence in these subjects, typically by earning a passing grade (usually a \"C\" or better) in each course. Additionally, the overall academic performance is part of the comprehensive evaluation that determines eligibility for graduation.\n\nThus, the minimum level of mathematical proficiency includes a strong understanding of calculus and introductory probability and statistics, as reflected in the successful completion of the core math courses.",
